#1 Recurrent rectal adenocarcinoma, previously resected node-negative
Prior to meeting with Mr. Palmer, I have had the opportunity to review his past medical records, laboratory tests, and imaging studies.  I have also had the opportunity to review this case in its entirety with his primary oncologist, Dr. Hubbard as well as with Dr. Price of the Colorectal Surgery Department.  At this time, we would like to further evaluate the liver lesions due to the fact that ultrasound did not see the lesions but feel that they continue to be indeterminate.  Therefore, after much discussion, it was decided to proceed with MRI scan for further delineation of this region.  Biopsy would be questionable in this situation due to the fact that he has a very small lesion.  He is scheduled to undergo simulation today.  I will be contacting the radiologists to let them know of our desire to further evaluate the liver before proceeding with such a heroic surgical procedure.  Patient stated full understanding and agreement with this plan.  I will see him back once MRI scan is completed.  He denies any further questions or concerns.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

[end section id="20112"]

